WEBVTT

00:00:03.260 --> 00:00:07.759
Looking at the brain from above, you can see a deep fissure called the longitudinal fissure,

00:00:08.099 --> 00:00:10.439
which divides the brain into two cerebral hemispheres.

00:00:11.300 --> 00:00:15.419
The surface of these cerebral hemispheres is riddled with many smaller fissures called

00:00:15.419 --> 00:00:16.059
sulcai.

00:00:16.920 --> 00:00:19.260
The ridges around those sulcai are called gyri.

00:00:20.480 --> 00:00:25.199
Sulcai and gyri are formed from the folding of the outermost layer of the brain, the cerebral

00:00:25.199 --> 00:00:25.679
cortex.

00:00:26.460 --> 00:00:31.160
The cerebral cortex contains important areas devoted to processing sensory information,

00:00:31.820 --> 00:00:36.439
important areas for movement, and what are known as association areas, which are regions

00:00:36.439 --> 00:00:41.340
where information from other brain areas is integrated to support higher level cognitive functions.

00:00:42.619 --> 00:00:47.320
The cerebral cortex is often divided into lobes, with the most common division being into

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:51.280
four lobes, frontal, parietal, occipital, and temporal.

00:00:51.960 --> 00:00:56.840
While each lobe contains numerous individual regions, we can identify some important areas

00:00:56.840 --> 00:00:59.060
for specific functions in each lobe.

00:00:59.939 --> 00:01:04.340
The frontal lobe, for example, contains the motor cortex, an area of the brain that's

00:01:04.340 --> 00:01:06.099
critically important for voluntary movement.

00:01:06.640 --> 00:01:10.420
The primary motor cortex makes up a large portion of the motor cortex.

00:01:11.400 --> 00:01:14.560
Neurons in the primary motor cortex cause movement in the head and body.

00:01:15.700 --> 00:01:19.579
The portion of the frontal lobe that's in front of the motor cortex is called the prefrontal

00:01:19.579 --> 00:01:19.939
cortex.

00:01:20.539 --> 00:01:25.680
The prefrontal cortex is particularly involved in higher level cognitive functions, including

00:01:25.680 --> 00:01:31.000
decision making, planning, impulse control, and the ability to act in pursuit of long-term

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:31.379
goals.

00:01:32.520 --> 00:01:35.980
Although there are a number of areas of the frontal lobe that are involved in language,

00:01:36.439 --> 00:01:40.939
one well-known language area is Broca's area, which is found in the left cerebral hemisphere

00:01:40.939 --> 00:01:41.780
in most people.

00:01:42.979 --> 00:01:46.799
The precise role of Broca's area in language is still being debated, but it's thought

00:01:46.799 --> 00:01:50.760
to be important for language production because damage to the region often disrupts the

00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:52.060
ability to produce language.

00:01:52.799 --> 00:01:57.459
A sulcus called the central sulcus separates the frontal lobe from the preital lobe.

00:01:58.120 --> 00:02:02.599
The preital lobe is involved with a number of functions, including language, spatial orientation

00:02:02.599 --> 00:02:08.139
and attention, and it also contains the primary somatosensory cortex, an area of the brain

00:02:08.139 --> 00:02:13.460
that's responsible for processing sensations from the body, such as touch, pain, temperature,

00:02:13.460 --> 00:02:16.979
and proprioception or awareness of the body's position in space.

00:02:18.260 --> 00:02:20.479
The occipital lobe is found at the very back of the brain.

00:02:20.900 --> 00:02:23.099
It's primarily associated with visual processing.

00:02:23.960 --> 00:02:28.819
The primary visual cortex, the main area for visual processing, is found here, along

00:02:28.819 --> 00:02:30.219
with several other visual areas.

00:02:31.400 --> 00:02:35.520
The temporal lobe is involved in a number of functions, including higher order processing

00:02:35.520 --> 00:02:38.740
of visual information, learning and memory, and hearing.

00:02:39.540 --> 00:02:44.439
It contains the primary auditory cortex, which plays a critical role in our ability to perceive sound.

00:02:45.539 --> 00:02:49.360
Near the junction between the temporal and preital lobes is another important language

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:50.840
area known as Vernicus area.

00:02:51.580 --> 00:02:55.800
Vernicus area is typically associated with language comprehension, although its contribution

00:02:55.800 --> 00:02:57.919
to language processing is still being explored.

00:02:59.080 --> 00:03:02.199
Extending from the very back and bottom of the brain is the cerebellum.

00:03:02.680 --> 00:03:06.539
The cerebellum is best known for its roles in movement, which include motor coordination

00:03:06.539 --> 00:03:12.240
and control, balance and posture, fine-tuning of voluntary movements, and movement-related

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:12.639
learning.

00:03:13.800 --> 00:03:17.639
When we look at a medial view of the brain, we can see a number of other structures that

00:03:17.639 --> 00:03:19.099
were obscured with a lateral view.

00:03:19.740 --> 00:03:24.120
We can, for example, clearly see the brainstem, which connects the brain to the spinal cord.

00:03:24.939 --> 00:03:28.319
The brainstem contains a number of important pathways that run between the brain and

00:03:28.319 --> 00:03:31.500
spinal cord, but it also has many important areas of its own.

00:03:31.500 --> 00:03:36.740
The brainstem is divided into three regions, the midbrain, ponds and medulla.

00:03:37.159 --> 00:03:42.120
The medulla, or medulla ablangada, is the lowest part of the brainstem found just above

00:03:42.120 --> 00:03:42.860
the spinal cord.

00:03:43.620 --> 00:03:47.860
One of the important roles linked to the medulla is the regulation of vital functions such

00:03:47.860 --> 00:03:50.000
as cardiovascular and respiratory activity.

00:03:50.659 --> 00:03:54.960
The ponds contains important pathways that carry information to and from the cerebellum,

00:03:55.240 --> 00:04:00.099
and is home to a number of nuclei or clusters of neurons associated with the cranial nerves,

00:04:00.819 --> 00:04:04.080
a group of nerves that are involved with sensory and motor functions of the head and

00:04:04.080 --> 00:04:04.520
face.

00:04:05.259 --> 00:04:07.879
The midbrain is the uppermost portion of the brainstem.

00:04:08.479 --> 00:04:11.740
The midbrain contains the two largest dopamine-producing areas in the brain.

00:04:12.439 --> 00:04:14.080
One is the substantiate nigra.

00:04:14.680 --> 00:04:17.860
Dopamine neurons here play important roles in movement, among other things.

00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:23.839
Large numbers of dopamine neurons in the substantiate nigra die in Parkinson's disease, leading to

00:04:23.839 --> 00:04:24.660
problems with movement.

00:04:25.660 --> 00:04:29.720
The other major dopamine-producing area in the midbrain is called the ventral-tegmental

00:04:29.720 --> 00:04:30.920
area or VTA.

00:04:31.800 --> 00:04:36.339
Dopamine neurons in the VTA extend to various parts of the brain, one of them being a region

00:04:36.339 --> 00:04:37.639
called the nucleus accumbens.

00:04:38.880 --> 00:04:43.519
This pathway between the VTA and nucleus accumbens seems to be critically important for rewarding

00:04:43.519 --> 00:04:46.259
experiences such as the use of addictive drugs.

00:04:47.500 --> 00:04:51.680
The substantiate nigra and nucleus accumbens are also part of a larger group of structures

00:04:51.680 --> 00:04:52.800
called the basal ganglia.

00:04:53.660 --> 00:04:57.819
The basal ganglia includes several other regions as well, and are involved in movement,

00:04:57.819 --> 00:05:01.699
habit formation, and reward processing, among other things.

00:05:02.959 --> 00:05:05.040
Above the brainstem is a structure called the phalamus.

00:05:05.920 --> 00:05:09.899
The phalamus is often described as a relay station, because a great deal of the information

00:05:09.899 --> 00:05:14.740
that proceeds to the cortex first stops the phalamus before being sent onto its destination.

00:05:15.600 --> 00:05:21.100
For example, all sensory information exceptal faction travels from sensory receptors to

00:05:21.100 --> 00:05:24.800
a nucleus in the phalamus specialized for dealing with that type of sensory data.

00:05:24.800 --> 00:05:29.839
Then the information is sent from the phalamus to the appropriate area of the cortex where

00:05:29.839 --> 00:05:30.920
it is further processed.

00:05:32.080 --> 00:05:36.319
Postearrier to the phalamus is the pineal gland, whose main function is to secrete the

00:05:36.319 --> 00:05:37.300
hormone melatonin.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:42.560
Melatonin plays an important role in regulating circadian rhythms and is primarily secreted

00:05:42.560 --> 00:05:43.160
during darkness.

00:05:44.519 --> 00:05:46.699
The hypothalamus is found just below the phalamus.

00:05:47.579 --> 00:05:51.399
The hypothalamus is involved in a long list of processes, many of which are critically

00:05:51.399 --> 00:05:55.360
important to maintaining homeostasis across various bodily systems.

00:05:56.439 --> 00:06:00.259
Some of the major functions generally attributed to the hypothalamus include the regulation

00:06:00.259 --> 00:06:06.019
of, thirst and drinking behavior, hunger and feeding, body temperature, stress responses,

00:06:06.620 --> 00:06:08.019
circadian rhythms, and more.

00:06:09.339 --> 00:06:13.100
One of the ways the hypothalamus helps to regulate all of these functions is through its

00:06:13.100 --> 00:06:18.480
connections to the pituitary gland, a hormone secreting gland that sits just below the hypothalamus.

00:06:19.079 --> 00:06:24.660
The pituitary gland produces a number of hormones, such as growth hormone, thyroid stimulating

00:06:24.660 --> 00:06:29.920
hormone, follicle stimulating hormone, and luteinizing hormone, which it releases in response

00:06:29.920 --> 00:06:31.519
to signals from the hypothalamus.

00:06:32.720 --> 00:06:37.920
The pituitary gland also secreates two hormones, oxytocin and vasopressin, which are made in

00:06:37.920 --> 00:06:42.220
the hypothalamus and sent down to the pituitary gland to be released into the bloodstream.

00:06:44.080 --> 00:06:47.620
The hippocampus is found in the temporal lobe, but was not visible with the lateral view

00:06:47.620 --> 00:06:50.180
of the brain we used earlier when discussing the temporal lobe.

00:06:50.899 --> 00:06:54.639
Typically, the hippocampus will be surrounded by brain tissue, but in this image, its

00:06:54.639 --> 00:06:56.060
approximate location is highlighted.

00:06:56.800 --> 00:07:00.399
The hippocampus has many functions, but is best known for its role in memory.

00:07:01.079 --> 00:07:04.839
It seems to be especially important for turning short-term memories into long-term memories.

00:07:06.259 --> 00:07:10.500
A adjacent to the hippocampus is the amygdala, an almond-shaped structure known for its

00:07:10.500 --> 00:07:11.100
role in emotion.

00:07:12.019 --> 00:07:16.300
The amygdala is most well known for processing fear and responding to threats in the environment,

00:07:17.100 --> 00:07:20.939
but it is also involved in other emotions, including positive emotions such as pleasure.

00:07:22.120 --> 00:07:24.899
This sea-shaped area is called the corpus colosum.

00:07:25.639 --> 00:07:30.240
The corpus colosum is the largest bundle of axons in the brain, and it connects the left

00:07:30.240 --> 00:07:34.040
and right cerebral hemispheres, enabling communication between them to occur.

00:07:35.780 --> 00:07:37.879
There is a system of cavities found throughout the brain.

00:07:38.379 --> 00:07:40.220
These hollow spaces are called ventricles.

00:07:41.060 --> 00:07:45.220
Specialized membranes in the ventricles produce cerebral spinal fluid, or CSF.

00:07:46.160 --> 00:07:48.860
CSF performs a number of important functions for the brain.

00:07:49.720 --> 00:07:54.060
For example, it surrounds the brain, forming a protective layer, and suspending the brain

00:07:54.060 --> 00:07:57.660
in fluid, which reduces the strain forces like gravity would have on the brain.

00:07:58.319 --> 00:08:02.259
It also removes waste products from the brain, and helps to regulate the extracellular

00:08:02.259 --> 00:08:03.339
environment of neurons.

